Paragraph

A paragraph (from the Greek paragraphos, "to write beside" or "written beside") is a self-contained unit of a discourse in writing dealing with a particular point or idea. A paragraph consists of one or more sentences. Though not required by the syntax of any language, paragraphs are usually an expected part of formal writing, used to organize longer prose.

HTML

									
										<p>A paragraph (from the Greek paragraphos, "to write beside" or "written beside") is a self-contained unit of a discourse in writing dealing with a particular point or idea. A paragraph consists of one or more sentences. Though not required by the syntax of any language, paragraphs are usually an expected part of formal writing, used to organize longer prose.</p>

Blockquote

A block quotation (also known as a long quotation or extract) is a quotation in a written document, that is set off from the main text as a paragraph, or block of text, and typically distinguished visually using indentation and a different typeface or smaller size quotation.

HTML

									
										<blockquote>
	<p>A block quotation (also known as a long quotation or extract) is a quotation in a written document, that is set off from the main text as a paragraph, or block of text, and typically distinguished visually using indentation and a different typeface or smaller size quotation.</p>
</blockquote>

The u element is text with an unarticulated, though explicitly rendered, non-textual annotation

The mark element indicates a highlight

	<p>The <i>i element</i> is text that is set off from the normal text</p>

	<p>The <u>u element</u> is text with an unarticulated, though explicitly rendered, non-textual annotation</p>

	<p><del>This text is deleted</del> and <ins>This text is inserted</ins></p>

	<p><s>This text has a strikethrough</s></p>

	<p>Superscript<sup>®</sup></p>

	<p>Subscript for things like H<sub>2</sub>O</p>

	<p>Abbreviation: <abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr></p>

	<p>Keybord input: <kbd>Cmd</kbd></p>

	<p><q cite="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/HTML/Element/q">This text is a short inline quotation</q></p>

Unordered

  • This is a list item in an unordered list
  • An unordered list is a list in which the sequence of items is not important. Sometimes, an unordered list is a bulleted list. And this is a long list item in an unordered list that can wrap onto a new line.
  • Lists can be nested inside of each other
    • This is a nested list item
    • This is another nested list item in an unordered list
  • This is the last list item

HTML

									
										<div class="text">
	<ul>
		<li>This is a list item in an unordered list</li>
		<li>An unordered list is a list in which the sequence of items is not important. Sometimes, an unordered list is a bulleted list. And this is a long list item in an unordered list that can wrap onto a new line. </li>
		<li>
			Lists can be nested inside of each other
			<ul>
				<li>This is a nested list item</li>
				<li>This is another nested list item in an unordered list</li>
			</ul>
		</li>
		<li>This is the last list item</li>
	</ul>
</div>

Ordered

  1. This is a list item in an ordered list
  2. An ordered list is a list in which the sequence of items is important. An ordered list does not necessarily contain sequence characters.
  3. Lists can be nested inside of each other
    1. This is a nested list item
    2. This is another nested list item in an ordered list
  4. This is the last list item

HTML

									
										<div class="text">
	<ol>
		<li>This is a list item in an ordered list</li>
		<li>An ordered list is a list in which the sequence of items is important. An ordered list does not necessarily contain sequence characters.</li>
		<li>
			Lists can be nested inside of each other
			<ol>
				<li>This is a nested list item</li>
				<li>This is another nested list item in an ordered list</li>
			</ol>
		</li>
		<li>This is the last list item</li>
	</ol>
</div>

Definition

Definition List
A number of connected items or names written or printed consecutively, typically one below the other.
This is a term.
This is the definition of that term, which both live in a dl.
Here is another term.
And it gets a definition too, which is this line.
Here is term that shares a definition with the term below.
And it gets a definition too, which is this line.

HTML

									
										<dl>
	<dt>Definition List</dt>
	<dd>A number of connected items or names written or printed consecutively, typically one below the other.</dd>
    <dt>This is a term.</dt>
    <dd>This is the definition of that term, which both live in a <code>dl</code>.</dd>
    <dt>Here is another term.</dt>
    <dd>And it gets a definition too, which is this line.</dd>
    <dt>Here is term that shares a definition with the term below.</dt>
    <dd>And it gets a definition too, which is this line.</dd>
</dl>

Blockquote With Citation

A block quotation (also known as a long quotation or extract) is a quotation in a written document, that is set off from the main text as a paragraph, or block of text, and typically distinguished visually using indentation and a different typeface or smaller size quotation.

Quote Source

</blockquote>

    Brazil Landing

    It starts with one act

    There are 400 million children living in poverty.
    One person's Act of Compassion is enough to impact a real change.

    From Now - March 27, 2016, the Compassion community is making a collective effort to raise money and help lift the milllions children in Brazil from poverty.

    • Start a fundraiser
    • Donate

    How does it work?

    • 80Acts of compassion started
    • $10,501Total amount
      raised

    Brazil is a country with a rich culture and strong faith, yet millions of Brazillian children live in extreme poverty and lack the resource to escape the cycle.

    Despite the adversities, Compassion International is helping children rewrite the story and rise above their cirumstances. These are stories of hope.

    Morgana
    Morgana's story is
    the story of her mother Rosilda

    Morgana

    2 years old

    Vitorino Freire, Maranhāo, Brazil

    Morgana seemed destined to live in abject poverty from the moment she was born. But instead of being haunted by misfortune and struggle, she now has the opportunity to break the chain of poverty and live a life that was denied to her mother, Rosilda.

    Through the help of Compassion, in partnership with the local church, Rosilda and her children have hope for a much brighter future. And thatâs something that didnât seem remotely possible not that long ago.

    To this day, Rosilda thinks about the decision she made 11 years ago, when she became pregnant as an 18-year-old. At the time she was unmarried and lived with her father, a man with a history of violence. Fearing for the safety of both herself and her unborn child, she moved to another city for the duration of the pregnancy, where a combination of despair and hunger ultimately led her to make the most difficult decision of her life: giving up her baby for adoption. âI didnât want to see my baby starve,â she said, âand I decided to leave him at the hospital and let them find a family for him.â The voice of the 29-year-old starts to quiver as she holds back tears. âI regret every single day.â

    Rosilda has since returned to her hometown of Virtino Freire, but rebuilding her life has been a struggle to say the least. The children she had while she was away â Morgana, now 2, and Dheric, now 3 months â are from two different men, both of whom dropped out of the picture immediately. So sheâs been alone, afraid and depressed from the moment she became a mother.

    But then Compassion came into her life and everything changed.

    Up to that point, she was lacking both the basic necessities (like diapers and clothing) and social support (she was alienated from her family and too discouraged to even talk with her neighbors) to raise her kids properly. Her situation, while heartbreaking, was very much the norm for mothers enrolled in Compassionâs Child Survival Program (CSP) at the local church, so the volunteers knew exactly what needed to be done in order to help Rosilda support her family.

    Immediately, they provided Rosilda, Morgana and Dheric with all their basic needs. Then, after lifting that enormous weight from Rosildaâs shoulders, they gently invited her to attend some of the lectures and courses that the program offers, where she ended up finding a community that offered support, guidance and companionship. What she treasures most today are the churchâs home visits, one of the pillars of the program. During these visits, program facilitators give the mothers personal lessons on a wide range of topics, from prenatal education and nutrition to Godâs love and the importance of prayer. âI can talk openly, ask questions. They give me ideas, they teach (me) personally.â

    âIâve got my 2 children, my treasures, and I love them. I needed strength to carry on â and Compassion helped me find that strength.â

    All in all, the program has been instrumental in helping Rosilda move past her depression, building up her confidence as both a mother and a person in the process. She now talks regularly with her neighbors, volunteers at the CSP, attends the partner church activities and sees to the needs of both Morgana and Dheric. Sheâs also learned to look towards the future instead of being stuck in the past. âI donât know where I would be at this point of my life without the programâs help,â she says. âIâve got my 2 children, my treasures, and I love them. I needed strength to carry on â and Compassion helped me find that strength.â

Then, after lifting that enormous weight from Rosilda’s shoulders, they gently invited  her to attend some of the lectures and courses that the program offers, where she ended up finding a community that offered support, guidance and companionship. What she treasures most today are the church’s home visits, one of the pillars of the program. During these visits, program facilitators  give the mothers personal lessons on a wide range of topics, from prenatal education and nutrition to God’s love and the importance of prayer. “I can talk openly, ask questions. They give me ideas, they teach (me) personally.”</p>
		</div>		
	</div>
</section> 

<section class="second">
	<img src="../../images/actbr_rosilda-4.png">
	<div class="row">
		<div class="columns max-45">
			<h2>“I’ve got my 2 children, my treasures, and I love them. I needed strength to carry on – and Compassion helped me find that strength.”</h2>
			<p>All in all, the program has been instrumental in helping Rosilda move past her depression, building up her confidence as both a mother and a person in the process. She now talks regularly with her neighbors, volunteers at the CSP, attends the partner church activities and sees to the needs of both Morgana and Dheric. She’s also learned to look towards the future instead of being stuck in the past. “I don’t know where I would be at this point of my life without the program’s help,” she says. “I’ve got my 2 children, my treasures, and I love them. I needed strength to carry on – and Compassion helped me find that strength.”
			</p>

    Threebrothers

    Lucas, Andre and Eudemar

    7, 10 and 11 years old

    Santa Rita, Pariba, Brazil

    For years, Lucas, Andre and Eudemar lived in constant fear of losing their father. A raging alcoholic, Eldir was often involved in street fights and regularly beat their mother, Jacqueline. âI wouldnât remember anything,â says Eldir, recounting some of his worst episodes.

    âThe boys were haunted, fearful of me, and I beat my wife many times.â

    The kids had already lost their grandfather to community violence and couldnât stand the thought of losing their father as well.

    But when Jacqueline started to volunteer at the local church, the boys found hope in the form of prayer, which they directed towards their fatherâs salvation. At every opportunity, they asked God to help break his destructive cycle of alcoholism, and eventually, He answered their prayers. One night during home worship, Eldir found the strength to replace alcohol with faith, and for the first time in their lives, the boys knew promise.

    Since then, the family has been an integral part of both Compassion and the local church community. Eldir participates in counseling and plays guitar at church services, Jacqueline continues to volunteer at the community center, and the three children are sponsored by the Child Development Sponsorship Program (CDSP).

    Where the brothers were once reserved, theyâve each found their respective voice through prayer and the supportive church community, which serves as a second family. Surrounded by loving âauntiesâ (female volunteers) who tend to them and caring âgodfathersâ (sponsors) who send them letters, the boys have blossomed into confident young men. Plus, theyâre fed regularly, receive quality medical care and are getting an education. In economically destitute Northeast Brazil, where half the kids between the ages of 15 and 17 arenât able to attend school and 20% of the adult population is illiterate, the brothers have a wonderful opportunity to rise above their situation. Lucas, the eldest child, wants to be a firefighter one day, and Compassion is giving him the tools and faith to make his dream a reality.

    "Every night we thank God for having saved our father"

    Meanwhile, a completely sober Eldir has found steady employment as a factory production assistant and is training to become a welder. Whatâs more, he even opened an ice cream shop next to their home as a way to generate additional income. Not too shabby! Apart from work, he and Jacqueline wed in the church and he now takes an active role in raising the boys. âEvery night we thank God for having saved our father,â says Lucas.

    Through sponsorship and the support of Compassion, and by accepting God into their lives, one familyâs cycle of addiction, poverty and hopelessness has come to an end â and thatâs a miracle to us.

	var _dashboardMessages = _dashboardMessages || new Array();
	//Add to the _dashboardMessages array to define messages for the page and when they're displayed.
	//Note that if you specify the percentages as null, they are simply ignored in the logic to display a message.
	//example: _dashboardMessages.push(new DashboardMessage(status, minPercentage, maxPercentage, message, rowClassName));
	_dashboardMessages.push(new DashboardMessage("Created", null, null, '<i class="fa fa-exclamation-circle"></i> Your fundraiser has not been launched.'));
	_dashboardMessages.push(new DashboardMessage("Suspended", null, null, "Your fundraiser has been suspended."));
	_dashboardMessages.push(new DashboardMessage("Active", 0, 0, "Be the first to donate and get the momentum rolling."));
	_dashboardMessages.push(new DashboardMessage("Active", 1, 35, "Don't forget to order/download your fundraiser materials."));
	_dashboardMessages.push(new DashboardMessage("Active", 36, 49, "Keep the momentum going."));
	_dashboardMessages.push(new DashboardMessage("Active", 50, 79, "Share your fundraiser to continue your successes."));
	_dashboardMessages.push(new DashboardMessage("Active", 80, 99, "You almost reached your goal—keep the momentum going."));
	_dashboardMessages.push(new DashboardMessage("Active", 100, 9999, "Congratulations! You reached your goal—keep it going."));
</script>

											function DisplayModal() {
												return 'True' == 'True';

											// register the modal dialog resize event.
											$(document).ready(function() {
												resetLoginOption(IsUserGuest());

												$('#rdoProfessed').colorbox({ iframe: true,
													width: 780,
													height: 500,
													maxWidth: '100%',
													maxHeight: '100%',
													href: 'https://local.compassion.com/cart/modal/Login.aspx'
												});

													$.colorbox({ iframe: true,
														width: 780,
														height: 500,
														maxWidth: '100%',
														maxHeight: '100%',
														href: 'https://local.compassion.com/cart/modal/Login.aspx'
													});
												}

												$(window).resize(function() {
													var frame = parent.frames[0];
													if (typeof (frame) != 'undefined' && typeof (frame.resize) == 'function') {
														frame.resize();
													}
												});
											});

											// set the login option.
											function resetLoginOption(isGuest) {
												if (isGuest) {
													var rdoGuest = $('#rdoGuest');
													if (rdoGuest.length != 0) {
														rdoGuest.get(0).checked = true;
													}
												}
												else {
													var rdoProfessed = $('#rdoProfessed');
													if (rdoProfessed.length != 0) {
														rdoProfessed.get(0).checked = true;
													}
												}
											}
										</script>

											<script type="text/javascript">
												//Get image submit button
												var imgSpecialInstructions = $('#imgSpecialInstructions');
												//Get the comments button
												var txtComments = $('#ctl00_cphPageTemplateContent_CheckoutInformation280_checkoutComments_txtComments');
												//Validate whether there is an error in the comments
												var validateHaveErrors = false;

												$(document).ready(function () {
													if (imgSpecialInstructions != null) {
														//Display the comments section when user input the comments before
														if (txtComments.val() != ''
														&& imgSpecialInstructions.hasClass('add-instructions')) {
															imgSpecialInstructions.removeClass('add-instructions');
															imgSpecialInstructions.addClass('remove-instructions');
															$('#commentsDiv').show();
														}

														//Hide and show the comments part
														imgSpecialInstructions.click(function () {
															if (imgSpecialInstructions.hasClass('add-instructions')) {
																//If the image is plus image, replace it to remove image and display the comments
																txtComments.val('');
																imgSpecialInstructions.removeClass('add-instructions');
																imgSpecialInstructions.addClass('remove-instructions');
																$('#commentsDiv').show(ieForceRedrawMinimal());
															}
															else if (imgSpecialInstructions.hasClass('remove-instructions')) {
																//If the image is remove image, replace it to plus image and hide and clear the comments
																imgSpecialInstructions.removeClass('remove-instructions');
																imgSpecialInstructions.addClass('add-instructions');
																txtComments.val('');
																$('#commentsDiv').hide(ieForceRedrawMinimal());
															}
															return false;
														});
													}
												});

												//validate comments field
												function validateComments() {
													//If Comments is displayed
													if (imgSpecialInstructions.hasClass('remove-instructions')) {
														validateHaveErrors = !validateTextArea(txtComments, $('#CommentsError'), false);
														if (validateHaveErrors) {
															return true;
														}
														else {
															return false;
														}
													}
												};
											</script>

										<script type="text/javascript">
											function IsUserGuest() {
												return 'True' == 'True';
											}
											function DisplayModal() {
												return 'True' == 'True';
											}

											// register the modal dialog resize event.
											$(document).ready(function() {
												resetLoginOption(IsUserGuest());

												$('#rdoProfessed').colorbox({ iframe: true,
													width: 780,
													height: 500,
													maxWidth: '100%',
													maxHeight: '100%',
													href: 'https://local.compassion.com/cart/modal/Login.aspx'
												});

												if (DisplayModal()) {
													$.colorbox({ iframe: true,
														width: 780,
														height: 500,
														maxWidth: '100%',
														maxHeight: '100%',
														href: 'https://local.compassion.com/cart/modal/Login.aspx'
													});
												}

												$(window).resize(function() {
													var frame = parent.frames[0];
													if (typeof (frame) != 'undefined' && typeof (frame.resize) == 'function') {
														frame.resize();
													}
												});
											});

											// set the login option.
											function resetLoginOption(isGuest) {
												if (isGuest) {
													var rdoGuest = $('#rdoGuest');
													if (rdoGuest.length != 0) {
														rdoGuest.get(0).checked = true;
													}
												}
												else {
													var rdoProfessed = $('#rdoProfessed');
													if (rdoProfessed.length != 0) {
														rdoProfessed.get(0).checked = true;
													}
												}
											}
										</script>

											<ul class="no-float clearfix">
												<li class="clearfix">
													<input class="check-input" id="rdoGuest" name="rdoLoginOption" value="New" type="radio" checked="checked" />
													<label for="rdoGuest">&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Yes</strong>, this is my first time giving to Compassion</label>
												</li>

												<textarea name="ctl00$cphPageTemplateContent$CheckoutInformation280$checkoutComments$txtComments" rows="4" cols="100" id="ctl00_cphPageTemplateContent_CheckoutInformation280_checkoutComments_txtComments" class="wi-text"></textarea>

											<script type="text/javascript">
												//Get image submit button
												var imgSpecialInstructions = $('#imgSpecialInstructions');
												//Get the comments button
												var txtComments = $('#ctl00_cphPageTemplateContent_CheckoutInformation280_checkoutComments_txtComments');
												//Validate whether there is an error in the comments
												var validateHaveErrors = false;

												$(document).ready(function () {
													if (imgSpecialInstructions != null) {
														//Display the comments section when user input the comments before
														if (txtComments.val() != ''
														&& imgSpecialInstructions.hasClass('add-instructions')) {
															imgSpecialInstructions.removeClass('add-instructions');
															imgSpecialInstructions.addClass('remove-instructions');
															$('#commentsDiv').show();
														}

														//Hide and show the comments part
														imgSpecialInstructions.click(function () {
															if (imgSpecialInstructions.hasClass('add-instructions')) {
																//If the image is plus image, replace it to remove image and display the comments
																txtComments.val('');
																imgSpecialInstructions.removeClass('add-instructions');
																imgSpecialInstructions.addClass('remove-instructions');
																$('#commentsDiv').show(ieForceRedrawMinimal());
															}
															else if (imgSpecialInstructions.hasClass('remove-instructions')) {
																//If the image is remove image, replace it to plus image and hide and clear the comments
																imgSpecialInstructions.removeClass('remove-instructions');
																imgSpecialInstructions.addClass('add-instructions');
																txtComments.val('');
																$('#commentsDiv').hide(ieForceRedrawMinimal());
															}
															return false;
														});
													}
												});

												//validate comments field
												function validateComments() {
													//If Comments is displayed
													if (imgSpecialInstructions.hasClass('remove-instructions')) {
														validateHaveErrors = !validateTextArea(txtComments, $('#CommentsError'), false);
														if (validateHaveErrors) {
															return true;
														}
														else {
															return false;
														}
													}
												};
											</script>

										</div>
										<div id="ctl00_cphPageTemplateContent_CheckoutInformation280_divBottomMessage" class="error-holder wi-message-bottom" style="display:none">
											<span id="ctl00_cphPageTemplateContent_CheckoutInformation280_lblBottomMessage" class="wi-error"></span>

    About Compassion Overlay

    ï»¿

    about compassion

    Releasing Children

    Founded by Rev. Everett Swanson in 1952, Compassion began providing Koren War orphans with food, shelter, education, and health care, as well as Christian training.

    1.6 million babies, children, and students released from poverty. And counting.

    Partnering with more than 6,000 local churches in 26 developing countries, Compassion International is the world's leading authority in child sponsorship.

    Our revolutionary approach to fighting poverty leverages local churches on the ground to provide critical resources and education while mentoring children to become responsbiel and fulfilled Christian adults.

    Former Compassion Children

    Peer-reviewed research published in the April 2013 issue of the Journal of Political Economy - one of the most prestigious economics journals in the world - concluded that Compassion's program has large and statistically significant impacts on the education, employment and leadership outcomes of our children.

    Education
    • 14% to 18% more likely to have salaried employment.
    • Roughly 35% more likely to secure white-collar employment as adults.
    Employment
    • 30% to 75% more likely to become commmunity leaders.
    • 40% to 70% more likely to become church leaders
    Leadership
    • 27% to 40% more likely to finish secondary education.
    • 50% to 80% more likely to complete a university education.
    • The impact of a sponosor
    • Compassion funding
    • Does it work? Research Findings.
    Mission Statment

    In response to the Great Compassion, Compassion International exists as an advocate for children, to released them from their spiritual, economic, social, and physical poverty and enable them to become responsible and fulfilled Christian adults.

    Our Commitment
    • To honor Jesus Christ in all that we do.
    • To work in partnership with the local church.
    • To directly impact each child's individual development.
    • To holistic child development -- developing minds, bodies, and spirits. To financial integrity and accountability. To give every child in our program a chance to respond to the gospel.

    We are grateful for your faithfulness and the work of our Christ-centered church partners around the world. In keeping with our commitment to transparency, here's how our funds wer utilized in the past fiscal year.

    PROGRAM EXPENSE

    Child Development Program

    Sponsor/Donor Ministries

    SUPPORTING SERVICES

    Administration

    Fundraising

    $596,909,822

    $561,374,252

    $35,535,570

    113,608,963

    $45,862,112

    $67,746,851

    TOTAL EXPENSES

    $710,518,785

    Charity Navigator, America's largest charity evaluator, has awarded Compassion its highest rating - four stars - for 14 consecutive years, placing Compassion in the top 1 percent of all charaties.

    What makes Compassion distinct:

    • 6,500 •

    International

    Church partners

    Invited Jesus to be their savior

    Toolkit Say Thanks

    Toolkit

    • get started
    • keep moving
    • finish strong
    • say thanks

    After all, they're the ones who made your fundraising campaign a success. So make sure to acknowledge their generosity with an email, a tweet, or by sharing their kindness somewhere else. And, of course, inspire them to get involved with Compassion at the same time!

	<script type="text/javascript">
		(function (u) {
			var d = document, s = 'script', a = d.createElement(s), m = d.getElementsByTagName(s)[0];
			a.async = 1; a.src = u; m.parentNode.insertBefore(a, m);
		})('//api.cloudsponge.com/widget/3d88d7d3477c0725506cb095f8d20fff6603c13f.js');

		// these values will hold the owner information
		var owner_email, owner_first_name, owner_last_name;
		var appendInTextarea = true;  // whether to append to existing contacts in the textarea
		var emailSep = ",";  // email address separator to use in textarea
		function populateTextarea(contacts, source, owner) {
			var contact, name, email;
			var emails = [];
			var textarea = document.getElementById('emailaddresses');

			// preserve the original value in the textarea
			if (appendInTextarea && textarea.value.strip().length > 0) {
				emails = textarea.value.split(emailSep);
			}
			// format each email address properly
			for (var i = 0; i < contacts.length; i++) {
				contact = contacts[i];
				email = contact.fullName() + " <" + contact.selectedEmail() + ">";
				if (emails.indexOf(email) < 0) {
					emails.push(email);
				}
			}
			textarea.value = emails.join(emailSep);

		}

		//Cloud Sponge Options
		var csPageOptions = {
			displaySelectAllNone: false,
			selectionLimit: '50',
			selectionLimitMessage: "The limit is 50 email addresses.",
			afterSubmitContacts: populateTextarea,
			sources: ["gmail", "yahoo", "windowslive", "aol", "outlook", "addressbook", "icloud", "csv"],
			csvProviders: {
				addressbook: true,
				outlook: true
			}
		};
	</script>

    Bio information is constructed by PowerBuilder upon consignment so it is not available with test data unless manually consigned in Compass in the test environment.
    Ika lives in the coastal community of Durian, home to approximately 3,200 residents. Typical houses are constructed of cement floors, brick walls and corrugated iron roofs. The primary ethnic group is Minahasa.

    The regional diet consists of fish and rice. Common health problems in this area include fevers, coughs and influenza. Adults in Durian work as day laborers and earn the equivalent of $56 per month. This community has electricity but needs improved sanitation, skills training and employment opportunities.

    Your sponsorship allows the staff of Teofani Student Center to provide Ika with Bible classes, nutritious food, medical checkups, sports, skills development and tutoring. The center staff will also provide meetings for the parents or guardians of Ika.
    Indonesia consists of 17,000 islands along the equator between Australia and Asia. The larger islands have central mountain ranges and fertile plains and lowlands. The climate is tropical with a rainy season from October to April.

    The country squeezes a population nearly the size of the United States into a landmass roughly triple the size of Texas; it has the fourth largest population in the world. Indonesia is also a diverse nation with many resources. More than 300 languages are spoken but the most common is Bahasa Indonesia. Islam claims 90 percent of Indonesians; however, Christianity, Hinduism, Buddhism and animism are also practiced.

    When Columbus sailed from Spain in 1492, he sought a new route to the Spice Islands of Indonesia. The Portuguese arrived in the sixteenth century but in 1602 the Dutch began slowly gaining control of the islands. Following Japanese occupation during World War II, the country, led by Sukarno, proclaimed independence in 1945. Suharto ousted Sukarno in 1967 and held the presidency of the military-controlled republic until 1998, when a collapsing economy fueled riots and demands for reforms. In 2001, the country elected a female leader, President Megawati Sukarnoputri.

This community has electricity but needs improved sanitation, skills training and employment opportunities.<br><br>Your sponsorship allows the staff of Teofani Student Center to provide Ika with Bible classes, nutritious food, medical checkups, sports, skills development and tutoring. The center staff will also provide meetings for the parents or guardians of Ika.
										</div>
										<div class="tab-bio clearfix ui-tabs-panel ui-widget-content ui-corner-bottom ui-tabs-hide" id="tab-3">
											Indonesia consists of 17,000 islands along the equator between Australia and Asia. The larger islands have central mountain ranges and fertile plains and lowlands. The climate is tropical with a rainy season from October to April.<br><br>The country squeezes a population nearly the size of the United States into a landmass roughly triple the size of Texas; it has the fourth largest population in the world. Indonesia is also a diverse nation with many resources. More than 300 languages are spoken but the most common is Bahasa Indonesia. Islam claims 90 percent of Indonesians; however, Christianity, Hinduism, Buddhism and animism are also practiced. <br><br>When Columbus sailed from Spain in 1492, he sought a new route to the Spice Islands of Indonesia. The Portuguese arrived in the sixteenth century but in 1602 the Dutch began slowly gaining control of the islands. Following Japanese occupation during World War II, the country, led by Sukarno, proclaimed independence in 1945. Suharto ousted Sukarno in 1967 and held the presidency of the military-controlled republic until 1998, when a collapsing economy fueled riots and demands for reforms. In 2001, the country elected a female leader, President Megawati Sukarnoputri.<br><br><br><br>

      Privacy And Conditions

      PRIVACY AND CONDITIONS OF USE

      Privacy Policy

      Conditions of use

      Compassion International online privacy statement

      Compassion International is committed to respecting your online privacy and security. We've structured our website so that, in general, you can visit us on the web without identifying yourself or revealing any personal information. Once you choose to provide us personally identifiable information (any information by which you can be identified), you can be assured that it will only be used to support your relationship with Compassion International.

      Awareness

      Compassion International provides this Online Privacy Statement to make you aware of our privacy policy and security practices, and to inform you about the way your information is collected and used. To make this notice easy to find, we make it available on our homepage and from the bottom of every Compassion International web page.

      Awareness

      On some Compassion International web pages you can become a sponsor, make donations, request materials or subscribe to magazines, emails or SMS text messages. The types of personal information collected on these pages are name, contact and billing information, transaction and credit card information. In order to tailor our subsequent communications to you and continuously improve our services, we may also ask you to provide us with information regarding your personal or professional interests, demographics, experiences as a sponsor, and contact preferences.

      How we use it

      Compassion International uses your information to understand your needs and provide you with better service. Specifically, we use your information to help you complete a transaction, communicate back to you, update you on your sponsored child and special events, and to personalize our website for you. Credit card numbers are used only for payment processing and are not retained for other purposes. From time to time, we may also use your information to contact you for market research or provide you with information we think would be of particular interest. At a minimum, we will always give you the opportunity to decline such direct marketing or market research contact. We will also follow local requirements, such as allowing you to opt in before receiving unsolicited contact, where applicable. Data collected online may also be combined with information you provide when you register online as a Compassion sponsor. We use 3rd-party demographic data (such as age, gender and interests) to better understand how our website is used and to make improvements in usability.

      Who we share it with

      Compassion International will not sell, rent, or lease your personally identifiable information to others. Unless we have your permission or are required by law, we will only share the personal data you provide online with Compassion International entities and/or business partners who are acting on our behalf to complete the activities described above. Such Compassion International entities and/or business partners, including those located in other countries, are governed by our privacy policies with respect to the use of this data.
